Jubilant astronomers saw decades of

work take wing Tuesday as the Hubble Space Telescope was boosted high above Earth to launch "a great adventure for mankind."
Charles Robert O'Dell, a Rice University space physicist who has worked 19 years on Hubble, said seeing it hurled into orbit aboard the shuttle capped an experience that was "comparable to raising a child.
I've been with the program since it was a concept.
Colin Norman, a physics and astronomy professor at Johns Hopkins University and academic affairs director of the Space Telescope Science Institute there, called the launch "the perfect start to a great adventure for mankind.
